<div class="container">
  <div class="page-head">
    <h1>Features</h1>
    <p class="lede">Cueport reads your Serato library on the Mac, mirrors a working set onto the iPhone over your local network, and plays from your local files. It does not require an internet connection or an account.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="feature-list">
    <article class="feature">
      <h3>Reads your Serato library</h3>
      <p>Link your <code>_Serato_</code> folder via the file picker. Cueport reads crates, subcrates, and tracks. Read-only toward your live Serato folder in this version.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="feature">
      <h3>Safety copies, automatically</h3>
      <p>After linking, Cueport makes a full duplicate of <code>_Serato_</code> into Application Support on a background thread. Re-linking the same path has a 24-hour cooldown.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="feature">
      <h3>Cue points from your MP3s</h3>
      <p>Hot cues are read from Serato Markers in MP3 ID3 frames. The cues you see in Cueport are the cues you set in Serato.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="feature">
      <h3>Local files, local playback</h3>
      <p>Player strip with audio playback from your local files. Paths resolve under the folder you granted. Nothing is uploaded.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="feature">
      <h3>Pick crates, send to iPhone</h3>
      <p>Choose some crates on the Mac, pair the iPhone with a QR code, and Cueport ships a working set over your local network for offline playback.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="feature">
      <h3>Track notes you can actually edit</h3>
      <p>Add notes to any track inline in the library. They save to the Serato Comment field on push, so they show up next to the track wherever Serato displays it.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="feature">
      <h3>Prep on the phone, sync back</h3>
      <p>New crates, moved tracks, and cue point updates made on the phone wait for your approval on the Mac before Cueport writes them back to Serato.</p>
    </article>
  </div>
</div>
